@EndNode

@Node About "Wot is it?"

@{b}So, what is it?@{ub}

	NewsAgent, is a utility for AmiTCP which allows you to interact with
an NNTP server, browsing though groups and articles, downloading only those
which appear to be of interest.  This is handy for getting the odd article
from those binary groups that you can't afford to subscribe to.  The articles
will be placed into a standard batch file, ready to be unbatched into the
relevant directory.  It features an easy to use GUI and lots of other good
stuff.

	NewsAgent requires AmiTCP v2.2 or above and access to an NNTP server.
It also requires AmigaDOS V2.04+ and something to @{" unbatch " LINK "unbatch"} news (you should
already have a copy of RNews, or perhaps DanNews).  A HardDrive and a wodge of
memory would probably be good plan.

@EndNode

@Node Install "Installing NewsAgent"

@{b}How to Install.@{ub}

	Installation is very simple.  

	To install, simply click on the Install-NewsAgent icon, and follow
the onscreen prompts.  It's all relatively painless.

	If you do not have Installer, you should FTP it from your favourite
Aminet site.  In the meantime, you can install it manually.

	Copy NewsAgent somewhere in your path, probably 'AmiTCP:bin'.  You
may also want to move the example Prefs file 'NewsAgentDefaults' to the
"uulib:" directory.  NewsAgent is now ready to @{" use " LINK "Usage"}.

@EndNode

@Node Usage "Using NewsAgent"

@{b}Using NewsAgent@{ub}

	After starting up TCP, simply run NewsAgent making sure you have set
your stack to at least 16k and specifying any @{" options " LINK "prefs"} for your setup.

	NewsAgent will attempt to make a connection to your NNTP server.  If
this is not successful, the server is probably down, or else NewsAgent cannot
resolve its address.  Depending on the options you have set, NewsAgent will
probably retry the connection a few times, in case the server was busy
(unless something more serious stops it).  If it can't connect after a few
tries, check that you can connect the server manually 'telnet SERVER nntp',
and if this is OK, check your @{" prefs " LINK "prefs"} again.

	If all is well, you should now be looking at the main NewsAgent
window.  This is made up of quite a few gadgets.  Theres the @{" Group " LINK "group"} button
and string gadgets, the @{" From " LINK "sliders"} and @{" To " LINK "sliders"} slider gadgets, the @{" wildcard " LINK "wild"}
selection gadgets.  The @{" subjects " LINK "subject"}, @{" articles " LINK "articles"}, and @{" filter " LINK "sort"} buttons.  Most
of the window is taken up by the @{" Subject list " LINK "sublist"} and underneath this is the
@{" Status-bar " LINK "bar"} and @{" Quit " LINK "quit"} button.
There is also now a @{" Post " LINK "posting"} button.

	There are also two menus available, which mirror some of the main
options.

	The first thing you should do is to select a @{" group " LINK "group"}

@EndNode

@Node group "Group gadgets"

@{b}Selecting a Newsgroup@{ub}

	There are two ways to select a newsgroup.  The simplest is just to
type its name into the string gadget at the top of the main window.

@{b}The Group Requester@{ub}

	A better way to choose newsgroups, is to use the group list, which
NewsAgent maintains.  Click on the 'group' button at the top left of the
window.  This will bring up the group selection requester.  From here you
can pick a group from an editable list as well as adding to and deleting
from the list.  The list is read when you run the program and written out
when you quit.  Every group you enter will be added to the list, but you
may edit it as you wish.  The group file may be selected using a preference
@{" setting " LINK "prefs"}

	The group requester has five gadgets.  The main gadget is a list of
newsgroups, which you can select from.  The current selection will be
highlighted as well as being copied to the string gadget at the bottom
of the screen.  'Delete' will remove the current selection from the list.
'Add' will add the contents of the string gadget to the list.  Duplicates
are not allowed.  'OK' or clicking on the close gadget, will shut the window
and put the current selection in the group string gadget, and attempting to
enter the group as if you had pressed return in the gadget.

@{b}Joining a Newsgroup@{ub}

	To actually join a group manually, press return in the string gadget.
NewsAgent will then request details of the group from the server.  If the
group is valid, the @{" sliders " LINK "sliders"} will be updated to represent the new group.
The 'To' gadget will be set to the last article.  The 'From' gadget will
either be set to the last article seen if the group is known, or to the last
article less 100 if it is not (or the server has renumbered the articles, and
NewsAgent gets lost).

	You should now select a @{" range " LINK "sliders"} of articles to review.

@EndNode

@Node sliders "Selecting a range of articles"

@{b}Article Ranges@{ub}

	In order to specify a range of articles to review, you should use the
To and From slider bars.  Simply drag the bars until the gadgets to the right
of them contain the desired article numbers.  The highest number is the last
article available.  NewsAgent will keep a record of the higest requested
subject in each group and automatically select all the new articles as the
default range.  If the sliders represent too large a range, you may find it
difficult to accurately set a range.  In this case simply type the article
numbers directly into the number gadgets at the side.

	Once the range is set, click on the @{" Subjects " LINK "subject"} button.

@EndNode

@Node subject "Subjects"

@{b}Subjects@{ub}

	The 'Subjects' button is used to request information on a range of
articles from the server, usually at least the subject header.  The
information will be formatted according the users @{" prefs " LINK "prefs"} and displayed
in the main @{" list " LINK "sublist"}

	Now look at the subject @{" list " LINK "sublist"} section.

@EndNode

@Node sublist "The Subject List"

@{b}Selecting Articles@{ub}

	The subject list displays information about the range of articles you
selected.  Exactly what is displayed depends on the user @{" prefs " LINK "prefs"}.  You
can select an article for downloading by clicking on it.  The article will be
indicated by a cross at the left.  Clicking again will deselect it.
All selected articles are stored in the Downloads window, so you can jump
back and forward between groups, making all the selections you want.  If you
re-enter a group you have selected articles from, they will still be
selected.

	After selecting, you may @{" download " LINK "articles"} your articles.

@EndNode

@Node articles "Downloading"

@{b}Downloading Articles@{ub}

	Hitting the articles button will open up the download selection 
window, or bring it to the front if it is already open.  From here, you can
initiate a download, view articles (useful for description files) and delete
articles from the download list.  Normally you would select all the headers
that look interesting from all your groups, and then come here to read
descriptions for any you're not sure about, filtering out articles as you go.

	The buffer size set in @{" preferences " LINK "prefs"} is the maximum size any article can be.
Any larger, and the article will be truncated.  If you are likely to be
downloading binaries, I would recommend setting this to be quite large (more
than 500000).  For text files, you may get away with a smaller buffer,
of under 64000.  It used to be the case that all large files were split up
into chunks less than 64k, but this is less common now.

	Alternatively, you can download with the 'binary' button.  Only use this for
a selection of binary articles though.  This will only work with binary
encoded articles.  Make sure also, that multi-part binaries are together and
in order in the list (tag them in this order, and they'll do fine).  With this
option,  the files will automatically be decoded on their way down, and will
be saved as binaries to the relevant directory set in the @{" preferences " LINK "prefs"}.
You can view these as they come down, they do not remain locked as the main batch
does.

	See also, the @{" Article Reader " LINK "reader"} page.

@EndNode

@Node reader "Reading Articles"

@{b}Reading.@{ub}

	Selecting read from the article list window, brings up a view of the
chosen article.  These windows are multi-threaded, and you can have as many
as is comfortable on your screen.  From these windows, you can traverse back
and forward through the list, as well as being able to display the 'parent'
article in the current thread, even if it is not in the selected list, or
the subject list.

	You can also choose to save this article (you will be prompted for a
filename), and @{" Reply " LINK "posting"}.

@EndNode


@Node sort "Filtering the List"

@{b}Filtering.@{ub}

NewsAgent has a simple Kill-file and sorting capability.  Clicking
on the filter gadget will bring up the filter window.  From here
you can control the filter options...

Subj, is a @{" pattern " LINK "wild"} to kill articles by.
Less, is a maximum article size to kill.
More, is a minimum article size to kill.

Only articles less than 'Less' and more than 'More' will be
affected by Subj.  If you want to affect all articles, simply
set Less to 0.

ID, is a @{" pattern " LINK "wild"} to kill article ID's by.
This is not affected by the Less and More settings.

Sort tells NewsAgent to sort the list alphabetically by
the subject.

Go, will perform the filter.

If you make a mistake, and filter out everything, just change
the filter settings and try again.  It doesn't forget all the
stuff it downloads, it just hides it.

@EndNode

@Node prefs "Preference Settings"

@{b}Setting up NewsAgent.@{ub}

	There are a number of configurable settings for NewsAgent, some of
which you will almost certainly have to, or at least want to change.  There
are three ways to choose a setting.  Most settings have reasonable built in
defaults.  If you want your own defaults, you can place them in the defaults
file which will override the built in settings.  Lastly you can specify
options on the command line.  An example default settings file is supplied,
which you can edit as required.  It comes with just the standard settings,
so if these are satisfactory you can leave it out.

For the position and sizes of the windows, and also to see the current
settings for all the options (even the ones with undefined defaults),
simply enter NewsAgent, set up all the windows how you like them.  Then
select 'Save Prefs' from the NewsAgent menu.  This will write out the
prefs file with all the current settings, including the window postioning.

	The defaults file is "UULIB:NewsAgentDefaults"

	The settings are [defaults]:-


@{b}HOST/SERVER <NAME>@{ub}		The name of your NNTP server.
				[news]

@{b}GROUP <NAME>@{ub}			The name of the default group.
				[alt.test]

@{b}BUFFER <SIZE>@{ub}			The size, in bytes of the buffer used when
				downloading news.  Should be a little bigger
				than the largest article. 
				[131072]

@{b}BATCHFILE <FILE>@{ub}		The filename of the batch file to write
				the articles to.
				[uuspool:NABatch]

@{b}WIDTH <SIZE>@{ub}			The desired width of the main window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}HEIGHT <SIZE>@{ub}			The desired height of the main window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}LEFT <POS>@{ub}			The position of the window's left edge.
				[far left of screen]

@{b}TOP <POS>@{ub}			The position of the window's top edge.
				[top of screen]

@{b}ARTOPEN@{ub}				If specified, will open the aricle window
				immediately.

@{b}ARTWIDTH <SIZE>@{ub}			The desired width of the article window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}ARTHEIGHT <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired height of the article window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}ARTLEFT <POS>@{ub}			The position of the article window's left edge.
				[far left of screen]

@{b}ARTTOP <POS>@{ub}			The position of the article window's top edge.
				[top of screen]

@{b}KILLOPEN@{ub}			If specified, will open the filter window
				immediately.

@{b}KILLWIDTH <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired width of the filter window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}KILLLEFT <POS>@{ub}			The position of the filter window's left edge.
				[far left of screen]

@{b}KILLTOP <POS>@{ub}			The position of the filter window's top edge.
				[top of screen]

@{b}GROUPWIDTH <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired width of the group window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}GROUPHEIGHT <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired height of the group window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}GROUPLEFT <POS>@{ub}			The position of the group window's left edge.
				[far left of screen]

@{b}GROUPTOP <POS>@{ub}			The position of the group window's top edge.
				[top of screen]

@{b}XOVER@{ub}				Enable use of the xover command for getting
				article information.  This returns more
				detailed article information including an
				exact article size.  No options, active if
				the setting is present.  To check is your
				server can use this command, telnet to your
				servers NNTP port ('telnet <SERVER> nntp')
				and type 'help'.  The server will then list
				the available commands.  If XOVER is present,
				then put this on a line in your defaults file.
				[]

@{b}GROUPFILE <FILE>@{ub}		The name of the file containing the newsgroup
				list.
				[uulib:NewsAgentGroups]

@{b}FORMAT <STRING>@{ub}			The format of the text display in the subject
				list.  This should be a string and can contain
				several special identifiers.  '%s' is the
				Subject: header, '%m' is the message ID,
				'%b' is the size in bytes, '%a' is the name
				of the author and '%n' is the article number.
				Please note that only %s and %n are available
				if you are not using the XOVER mode.
				["{%n:%b} %s"]

@{b}RETRY <TIMES>@{ub}			The number of times to retry the server, if it is
				not available immediately.
				[5]

@{b}OPENSCREEN@{ub}			If specified, NewsAgent will open its own screen
				for its windows.

@{b}DISPLAY <MODEID>@{ub}		Specifies the ModeID of the NewsAgent screen,
				if you also use 'OPENSCREEN'.  Typical
				values, are: 32768 (for Hires), and 32772
				for HiresLace.  Productivity is 233508.  You
				should not specify other values for this
				yourself unless you know exactly what you
				are doing.  If you have WB2.1 or higher,
				NewsAgent has a screen-mode requester for
				you to select the correct mode for your
				system.
				[32768]

@{b}FONT <FONTNAME>@{ub}			Allows you to select a font for
				NewsAgent to display its gadget imagery
				in (including the subject list).  Normally
				reads something like 'FONT topaz.font'.
				If this has not been set, NewsAgent will try
				to use your proportional system font. If
				either of these fonts are not suitable (too
				large etc.), NewsAgent will fall back to
				topaz.

@{b}FONTSIZE <SIZE>@{ub}			The size of font to use if using 'FONT'.
				[8]

@{b}KILLSUB <PATTERN>@{ub}		Pattern to kill subjects by (see @{" Filter " LINK "sort"})
				[nothing]

@{b}KILLID <PATTERN>@{ub}		Pattern to kill article ID's by (see @{" Filter " LINK "sort"})
				[nothing]

@{b}LESSTHAN <SIZE>@{ub}			Maximum article size to be affected by kill
				subject pattern.

@{b}MORETHAN <SIZE>@{ub}			Minimum article size to be affected by kill
				subject pattern.

@{b}VIEWWIDTH <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired width of the article viewer window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}VIEWHEIGHT <SIZE>@{ub}		The desired height of the article viewer window.
				[Depends on Font]

@{b}WRAP <SIZE>@{ub}			The maximum length of a line of text before it
				will be word-wrapped.
				[75]

@{b}REPLY <SIZE>@{ub}			The contents of the reply field in posted articles, if
				not to be taken from the environment.
				[$USER@$HOSTNAME]

@{b}BINDIR <SIZE>@{ub}			Where to put decoded binary files.
				[UUSPOOL:]

@{b}PUBSCREEN <SIZE>@{ub}		Name of a public screen to open on.
				[Workbench]



@EndNode

@Node wild "Wildcards"

@{b}Wildcard Selections.@{ub}

	Wildcards can be used to select and deselect articles in the subject
list.  Simply enter the selection string into the wildcard gadget, and either
press 'In' to select all the matching articles, or 'Out' to deselect them.

There are two wildcards available, '*' represents any combination of
characters, including the empty string, and '?' represents any single
character.

Multiple wildcard can be selected by seperating them with a '|'
character:-

*test*|*re:*

If you want to use one of these special characters in your wildcard
string as a real character, precede it with a backslash '\\'

@EndNode

@Node bar "Status"

@{b}Status Bar.@{ub}

	The status bar is used to display messages as the program is running.
It is here that reports as to what the program is up to will be displayed.

@EndNode

@Node quit "Quitting"

@{b}Quitting NewsAgent@{ub}

	You can quit NewsAgent, by either clicking on the 'Quit' gadget or
closing the main window.  After quitting, you'll probably need to @{" unbatch " LINK "unbatch"}
your articles.

@EndNode

@Node unbatch "Unbatching"

@{b}Unbatching the News.@{ub}

	To get the articles into a form readable by your news reader, you need
to unbatch them.  This is simply a case of typing 'RNews UUSpool:NABatch' if
you have not changed the setup.  Obviously if you use a different unbatcher,
or have moved your batch file you will have to alter this accordingly.

	If you are not subscribed to a group that an article belongs to, the
unbatcher will normally put it in 'junk', so you may need to subscribe to this
group.  See your newsreaders documentation for details.

	Bear in mind, the the batch file is basically a text file, so if all
you have downloaded is text, then there is nothing to stop you from reading
it with your favourite text editor/viewer.

@EndNode

@Node future "Tommorows World"

@{b}Possible Additions for Future Versions.@{ub}

	There are several things I'd like to put in but haven't had the time
(if I kept holding back to put something else in, you'd never see the thing).
If there is something on this list that you want, feel free to express your
support.  If there is something you want which is not on this list, please
drop me a line (or preferably an EMail), and I'll consider it.  Some of the
features in the program already, are suggestions from other people.

	@{b}The ability to do selections off-line.@{ub}  The is complicated for a
		number of reasons, and is something I don't really relish the
		idea of doing.  On the other hand, everybody wants it...
		This will be put in, in the next version.

	@{b}Proper full group list.@{ub}  Yes, I'll do this.

@EndNode


@Node posting "Article posting"

@{b}Posting news with NewsAgent.@{ub}

	NewsAgent 1.4 can now post articles.  This means you can make
	contributions to Usenet, as well as follow up other peoples
	posts.  Bear in mind though, that the posting facilities are
	very basic.  This version of NewsAgent is not intended as a
	newsreader, though it can be used as such.
	
	To post, simply hit the Post button on the main window, or
	the Reply button on an article window.  This will trigger
	your editor (Which should be set up in the environment variable
	'Editor' ).  Once you have composed your article, quit the
	editor, and NewsAgent will confirm your action, and then 
	try to post, direct to the server with NNTP.  If the server
	does not support posting, you will have to use another one,
	or post via a more traditional method.

@EndNode
